[2] Japan
Date: Sat 31 Dec 2022
Source: Yomiuri Shimbun Online [in Japanese, machine trans., edited]
https://news.yahoo.co.jp/articles/6785c7199a6f6a7354bf36483619e620a541b6dc


Highly pathogenic avian influenza is raging on farms and facilities across the country this season. Since the end of October [2022], both the number of cases and the number of slaughtered cases have increased at a record high, and it was also confirmed for the 1st time in 5 prefectures where there had been no cases of infection at poultry farms. The national government has begun emergency disinfection on a nationwide scale, but local governments responsible for slaughtering large numbers of chickens are screaming that they are "beyond the scope of what they can handle," and concerns are spreading among poultry farmers.

"[The culling] is out of the hands of local governments alone. I would like to ask you to consider revising the way of thinking so far." On the 21st of this month, Governor Kazuhiko Oigawa of Ibaraki Prefecture, which boasts the highest egg production in Japan, appealed to Minister of Agriculture Nomura at the minister's office of the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries in Kasumigaseki, Tokyo.

In Ibaraki Prefecture, on 4 Nov 2022, an outbreak of bird flu occurred at a poultry farm in Kasumigaura City. It took 19 days to kill, bury, incinerate, and disinfect 1.03 million egg-laying hens. The mobilization of prefectural officials (5350 in total), including those from departments unrelated to livestock farming, and the Self-Defense Forces (1100 in total) dispatched to disaster areas were not enough. also recruited [?].

Governor Oigawa has told Minister of Agriculture Nomura to oblige large-scale farms to secure workers in advance and prepare lime for disinfection and protective clothing at their own expense, in consideration of poultry farms with more than 500 000 chickens. He requested that these should be included in the national guidelines.

At the press conference after the cabinet meeting on the 27th [Dec 2022], Agriculture Minister Nomura said, "Now is the real time, so we must respond with a sense of urgency."

This season, at farms and facilities in Japan, infections were confirmed for the 1st time in Okayama Prefecture and Hokkaido on 28 Oct [2022]. On 30 Dec [2022], new infections were found in Saitama and Hiroshima prefectures, bringing the total number of cases in 22 prefectures to 51 as of the same day. Of these, 5 prefectures -- Yamagata, Fukushima, Tottori, Nagasaki, and Okinawa -- are the 1st cases to be reported. A total of 7.72 million birds nationwide are subject to culling. Both the number of outbreaks (52 cases in 18 prefectures) and culling (9.87 million birds) are likely to surpass the record highs between November 2020 and March 2021.

In Aomori Prefecture, 1.39 million egg-laying hens raised at a poultry farm in Misawa City were culled over the course of 2 weeks from the 15th of this month [December 2022]. This is the highest number ever for a single location. Ken Sasaki, chairman of the prefectural poultry farming association in Hachinohe, said, "We don't know when and where it will occur, so we have to rely on God in the end."

Bird flu spreads when migratory birds carrying the virus migrate south from their nesting grounds in Siberia, Russia, to overwinter. Wild birds are infected with the virus and introduce it into poultry farms. Therefore, in Japan, the season for outbreaks is from late autumn to spring. However, in Europe outbreaks continued throughout the summer [of 2022], albeit infrequently, and the 'off-season' has disappeared. French farms have confirmed 1487 infections in just over a year since October last year [2021].

Hiroki Takakuwa, professor of veterinary microbiology at Kyoto Sangyo University, said, "This season, infected wild birds were found as early as late September in Japan. Migratory birds spread the virus to various parts of the country much earlier than usual."

This autumn, Kyoto Prefecture drained water from 65 reservoirs and installed nets to prevent wild birds from approaching. There is an analysis by the Agriculture and Food Research Organization (Ibaraki Prefecture) that there is a high risk of infection at poultry farms within about 100 m [328 ft] of ponds and watersides such as rivers.

According to JA Zennoh Egg (Tokyo), the wholesale price of chicken eggs has been above average since this spring due to the impact of soaring mixed feed prices due to the invasion of Ukraine. This month's [December 2022's] average was 284 yen [USD 2.15] per kg [2.2 lb] for M size (Tokyo area), the highest monthly average since 1993, when wholesale prices were published. In addition to the peak demand for Christmas and New Year holidays, "the bird flu definitely pushed up prices," industry insiders said.

The price rise is expected to come to a halt after the New Year, when demand will settle down, but an official from the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries said, "It is necessary to carefully monitor trends, considering the infection situation."

According to Zen-Noh Egg, the expiration date printed on egg packs is "the period during which the eggs can be eaten raw." If you keep it in the refrigerator, you can heat it up and eat it for a few days even after the expiration date. It is said that quality deterioration is less likely to progress if the sharp side of the shell is placed downward.

