[3] Israel
Date: Tue 3 Jan 2023
Source: The Jerusalem Post [abridged, edited]
https://www.jpost.com/health-and-wellness/article-726530


Outbreaks of avian influenza were found at farms in Be'er Tuvia, southern Israel [25 000 broiler breeding stock], and Magal, central Israel [20 000 turkeys], the Agriculture Ministry announced on Tue [3 Jan 2023].

About 25 000 turkeys are housed in Magal and about 25 000 chickens in the Be'er Tuvia farm. All were infected with the H5N1 strain of the virus.

All coops within 10 km [6.2 mi] of the outbreaks were placed on lockdown.

The Agriculture Ministry advised anyone who owns birds or poultry to keep the birds kept inside buildings and to prevent them from going outside in order to prevent the spread of the virus.

The Agriculture Ministry stressed that it is still safe to purchase poultry and eggs. They should be cooked to completion before consumption.

The outbreaks are the 5th and 6th detected in Israel this season.

Late December 2022, Israeli officials reported to the World Organization for Animal Health that a Dunlin bird, found dead [in central Israel], was infected with the same H5N1 strain of the virus identified in another wild bird at the Hula Lake in northern Israel [on 29] Nov 2022.

The 1st outbreak of the season, in November 2022, was reported at a turkey slaughterhouse, in animals transported from Kibbutz Shluhot in northern Israel.

[During the winter 2021/2022], a large outbreak of H5N1 avian influenza swept through Israel. For the 1st time, the virus caused mass mortality among wild birds, killing some 8000 cranes in the Hula Lake area [north-east Israel] and leading to the death and culling of about a million farmed poultry, in 20 hotspots across the country.

The new cases in Israel come amid an ongoing outbreak in North America and Europe that started in 2021 and has been described as "the largest-ever" outbreak on both continents.

[Byline: Tzvi Joffre]

--
