******
[7] South Korea
Date: Sun 1 Jan 2023
Source: Yonhap via The Korea Herald [edited]
https://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20230101000069


South Korea has confirmed a new case of avian influenza at a duck farm in a southern region, local officials said Sunday [1 Jan 2023].

The highly pathogenic avian influenza strain of H5N1 was found at the farm located in Jeongeup, North Jeolla Province, according to the officials.

The new case brought the total bird flu infections confirmed in the province this winter to 4.

About 15 000 ducks have been culled at the farm and those located nearby. Local authorities have enforced restrictions on vehicles moving in and out of the affected area for 24 hours as part of preventive measures.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[ProMED map of South Korea: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8707631,195]

[According to WOAH's most recent periodic update of avian influenza, covering the period 11 Nov - 1 Dec 2022, the current HPAI epidemic season continues in an increasing rate, mainly in Europe and also in the Americas and Asia. Many of the countries in these regions are experiencing a larger number of outbreaks compared to last year's [2022's] wave at the same time. Outbreaks are also spreading further to South America countries. The predominant subtype noticed in the current epidemic season is still subtype H5N1. "Based on the HPAI seasonal pattern, the number of outbreaks in animals is expected to raise in the coming months." This forecast, published early December 2022, seems to have been, unfortunately, accurate, as apparent from the above reports, in particular, the Japanese one.

The World Organisation for Animal Health (WOAH) recommended that countries maintain their surveillance efforts and biosecurity measures at farm level and continue timely reporting of avian influenza outbreaks in both poultry and non-poultry species. High-quality information is key to support early detection and rapid response to potential threats to both animal and public health. - Mod.AS]
